A rather arbitrary threshold of .4 to include bad luck participants which might have encountered a long train of mismatch trials. I should probably re-consider this.

# Poor performers
poor_performers <- agg_data$participant[agg_data$mean_acc < .4]

# Remove poor performers
full_data <- full_data %>%
  filter(!(participant %in% poor_performers))

# Aggregate
agg_data <- full_data %>% 
  group_by(participant, changeness) %>% 
  summarise(mean_acc = mean(cd_acc),
            sd_acc = sd(cd_acc))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'participant'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Plot clean sample
ggplot(data = agg_data,
       mapping = aes(x=changeness, y = mean_acc, color = changeness)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_jitter(shape=10, position=position_jitter(0.2)) +
  ylab("Mean acc") + 
  ylim(c(0,1.1)) +
  labs(title = paste("Overall acc"))

After removing bad performers, we can aggregate by congruity and scene type to look at performance. We will first code the scene type in two sparse vs cluttered

# Aggregate
agg_data <- full_data %>% 
  filter(changeness == "change") %>% 
  group_by(participant, congruity, clutter) %>% 
  summarise(mean_acc = mean(cd_acc),
            sd_acc = sd(cd_acc))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'participant', 'congruity'. You can
## override using the `.groups` argument.
# Plot
make_plot(agg_data, agg_data$mean_acc, "Mean acc by congruity")

Compute performance at encoding

And now look at performance as RTs

# Aggregate
agg_data <- full_data %>% 
  filter(changeness == "change", cd_acc == 1) %>% 
  group_by(participant, congruity, clutter) %>% 
  summarise(mean_rt = mean(cd_rt, na.rm = T),
            sd_rt = sd(cd_rt, na.rm = T))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'participant', 'congruity'. You can
## override using the `.groups` argument.
# Plot
make_plot(agg_data, agg_data$mean_rt, "Mean RT by congruity")

Detection efficiency

Lets compute the detection efficiency index

# Compute as acc/RT
agg_data <- full_data %>% 
  filter(changeness == "change") %>% 
  group_by(participant, congruity, clutter) %>% 
  summarise(mean_acc = mean(cd_acc), sd_acc = sd(cd_acc),
            mean_rt = mean(cd_rt, na.rm = T), sd_rt = sd(cd_rt, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  mutate(eff_ind = mean_acc/mean_rt) %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'participant', 'congruity'. You can
## override using the `.groups` argument.
# Plot
make_plot(agg_data, agg_data$eff_ind, "Mean efficiency by congruity")

Compute rANOVA

I will compute a 2x2 repeated measures ANOVA with scene-object congruity (congruent vs.incongruent) and trial type (cluttered vs.sparse) as within-subjects factors.

# Need to select only the to-be-used columns
data_to_stat <-  subset(x = agg_data, select = c(participant, congruity, clutter, eff_ind))

# Run ANOVA
res.aov <- anova_test(data = data_to_stat, dv = eff_ind, wid = participant, within = c(congruity, clutter))
get_anova_table(res.aov)
## ANOVA Table (type III tests)
## 
##              Effect DFn DFd      F        p p<.05   ges
## 1         congruity   1  17 17.683 5.95e-04     * 0.036
## 2           clutter   1  17 61.741 4.66e-07     * 0.386
## 3 congruity:clutter   1  17  4.254 5.50e-02       0.011
# Pair-wise comparisons
pwc <- data_to_stat %>%
  group_by(clutter) %>% 
  pairwise_t_test(
    eff_ind ~ congruity, paired = TRUE,
    p.adjust.method = "bonferroni"
  )
pwc
## # A tibble: 2  11
##   clutter   .y.     group1 group2    n1    n2 statis    df     p p.adj p.adj
## * <fct>     <chr>   <chr>  <chr>  <int> <int>    <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <chr>  
## 1 cluttered eff_ind con    inc       18    18    -3.90    17 0.001 0.001 **     
## 2 sparse    eff_ind con    inc       18    18    -1.50    17 0.151 0.151 ns     
## #  with abbreviated variable names statistic, p.adj.signif

Identification

# Aggregate
agg_data <- full_data %>% 
  filter(changeness == "change") %>% 
  filter(cd_acc == 1) %>% 
  group_by(participant, congruity, clutter) %>% 
  summarise(mean_id = mean(id_acc, na.rm = T),
            sd_id = sd(id_acc, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'participant', 'congruity'. You can
## override using the `.groups` argument.
# Plot

Recognition

  filter(cd_acc == 1) %>% 
  group_by(participant, congruity, clutter) %>%
